Problem Statement¶

About data

The "Cerebral Stroke Prediction" dataset is a real-world dataset used for the task of predicting the occurrence of cerebral strokes in individuals. The primary goal of this dataset is to develop a predictive model that can identify individuals who are at a higher risk of suffering a cerebral stroke. Early detection and intervention can be critical in reducing the severity and consequences of strokes.

Please find the data in the drive: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1jeZjNxUxaxUEn1J57QKcmlT3l4yYZrMj/view?usp=sharing

Objective:

In this assignment, you will work with the "Cerebral Stroke Prediction" dataset, which is characterized by class imbalance. Your goal is to develop a machine learning model to predict the occurrence of cerebral strokes and evaluate its performance while addressing the class imbalance challenge.

Problem statement:

What are the main factors that contribute to stroke occurrence in the dataset? Can we effectively identify individuals at risk of experiencing cerebral strokes based on their attributes? How well does the model perform in detecting stroke occurrence while considering the class imbalance? How can healthcare providers use the model's predictions to improve patient care and reduce the risk of strokes?

Outcome Variable:

The target variable is binary and indicates whether a patient had a stroke (positive class) which is denoted with 1 or did not have a stroke (negative class) is denoted with 0.

Model Evaluation:

Evaluate the performance of each model using the testing dataset. Calculate the following metrics:

Accuracy Sensitivity Specificity

Submission Guidelines:

Prepare a Jupyter Notebook or a well-documented Python script that contains your data preprocessing, model building, and evaluation code. Include explanations and comments in your code to ensure clarity. Submit the assignment as a report or presentation, summarizing the key findings and recommendations.

Tips: Use the proper sampling technique, Hyperparameter Tuning to run the ML Algorithm to achieve outcome variable.

# Write a function & call to check accuracy score of different model

def metric_score (clf, x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test, train=True):
    if train:
        y_pred=clf.predict(x_train)
        
        print("\n =============Train Result===============")
        print(f"Accuracy score:{accuracy_score(y_train, y_pred)*100:.2f}%")
        
    elif train==False:
        pred=clf.predict(x_test)
        
        print("\n =============Test Result================")
        print(f"Accuracy score:{accuracy_score(y_test, pred)*100:.2f}%")
        
        print("\n \n classification report \n", classification_report(y_test, pred, digits=2))

Conclusion¶

In [ ]:
#The peoples having higher hypertension they have higher chances of strokes.
#Also the peoples having heart disease they have chances of stroke.
#Peoples whose glucose level is more than 140 having highetr chances of strokes.
#Peoples whose age between 60 to 80 having more chances of strokes.Very few peoples age between 40 to 60 years having chances of strokes.
#Peoples whoes age between 0 to 40 having very rare chances of strokes.
#Higher bmi does not mean person get stroke.

What are the main factors that contribute to stroke occurrence in the dataset?¶

Mainly the people having hypertension, Heart disease, higher glucose level(More than 150) & the people whose age between 60 to 80 years having higher chances of strokes.

Can we effectively identify individuals at risk of experiencing cerebral strokes based on their attributes?¶

Mainly hypertension, high glucose level & heart disease patients are having higher chances. But the people who are working in private sector & selg employed having higher chances of strokes this may be due to work pressure.

How well does the model perform in detecting stroke occurrence while considering the class imbalance?¶

Data set is imbalanced hence first it has been balanced by using SMOTE oversampling techniques. With the help of oversamling we can not loose valuable dataset. Model performing very well in kNN algorithm because in confusion matrix false negative ratio is zero & false positive is very less.Model is performing very well in True positive & True negative. Area under the curve is almost 97%. Accuracy score: 97%, precision, recall & f1 score : 98%. Hence it is the best model for prediction.

How can healthcare providers use the model's predictions to improve patient care and reduce the risk of strokes?¶

Above model is highly precise whose accuracy is 97% hence we can easily indetify the chances of strokes after getting all the necessary details of person like hypertension, glucose level, age, bmi, heart disease.
